    "text": "Honest answer: your data can't say yet. There isn't an established, statistically gated pattern between alcohol and HRV in your history — not because the effect isn't real, but because too few drinking days are tagged to compare against sober ones. And right now nothing looks off: your HRV is 62 ms, close to your 30-day average of 62.6 ms, and your recovery score is 69%, essentially at your 7-day average recovery of 70%. Alcohol does reliably suppress overnight HRV in population studies, but whether and how much it hits you personally is exactly what tagging would reveal. The single useful action: log drinks on the nights you have them for the next month. After roughly 10 tagged weekends, the comparison can be run on your own mornings instead of a hunch.",
